d hateful words. Maurissa tears up on the apology for issues on diversity, stating it would get accepted as sooner.\n| LineColor       = 141921\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Bachelor (season 24)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 250\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 11\n| Title           = Week 10: Season Finale\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|9}}\n| ProdCode        = 2410A\n| Viewers         = 7.70<ref name=\"24.11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-monday-cable-originals-network-finals-3-9-2020.html|title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Monday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 3.9.2020|last=Metcalf|first=Mitch|date=March 11, 2020|work=Showbuzz Daily|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n| Aux4            = 2.1/11<ref name=\"24.11\"/>\n| ShortSummary    = Peter and the final two ladies traveled to [[Alice Springs]] as he has an opportunity to introduce them to his family. Hannah Ann comes in first to meet with Peter's family and opens up about the first impression rose during the first night and talk along with the potential in-laws. The next day, when Madison comes in to meet with Peter's family, Madison gives Peter to talk to him, and how she happened during the overnight dates, Madison feels giving her appreciation to make next step towards love, she is feeling anxious to see Peter's parents once again as the last time was on the first one-on-one date, Peter's mom Barbara is giving a concern on Madison and is felt on proving to be a potential daughter-in-law. When Madison left, Peter and his mother are talking each other as Barbara consoles her gratitude and said, \"Don't let her go!\", stating that Madison would bring to Peter's family.\n\nMadison's final date takes on an airplane ride onto the overlooking with the famous [[Uluru]] and even they have set up a picnic. When Madison becomes emotional and frustrated that she doesn't think her romance where she belongs, felt her chemistry loosened and Madison leaves the show. Hannah Ann's final date is to travel to The Kangaroo Sanctuary as she and Peter are carrying kangaroos and each person fed a drink to feed. Hannah Ann is equally showing her heart with Peter and stated that proving the relationship would get some answers, as the show ends here.\n| LineColor       = 141921\n}}\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Bachelor (season 24)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 251\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 12\n| Title           = After the Final Rose\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|10}}\n| ProdCode        = 2410B\n| Viewers         = 8.49<ref name=\"24.12\">{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-tuesday-cable-originals-network-finals-3-10-2020.html|title=Updated: ShowBuzzDaily's Top 150 Tuesday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 3.10.2020|last=Metcalf|first=Mitch|date=March 11, 2020|work=Showbuzz Daily|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n| Aux4            = 2.4/12<ref name=\"24.12\"/>\n| ShortSummary    = \n| LineColor       = 141921\n}}\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\nDuring week five, contestant Victoria Fuller won a group date challenge, where she was chosen to appear on the March digital cover of ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'' with Weber. Shortly after the episode that featured Fuller's win aired, ''Cosmopolitan'' editor-in-chief [[Jessica Pels]] \u2013 who appeared in the episode and selected Fuller as the winner \u2013 published an online letter which stated that the magazine would not be running the cover with Fuller, due to Fuller's involvement with a clothing brand that featured a \"[[White Lives Matter]]\" tagline.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/2020/02/04/cosmopolitan-pulls-its-digital-cover-with-bachelor-contestant-victoria-fuller/|title=Cosmopolitan pulls digital cover with \u2018Bachelor\u2019 contestant Victoria Fuller over her \u2018white lives matter\u2019 ad|last=Bonos|first=Lisa|date=February 4, 2020|website=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the letter, Pels stated that \"unequivocally, the White Lives Matter movement does not reflect the values of the ''Cosmo'' brand,\" adding \"we stand in solidarity with [[Black Lives Matter]], and any cause that fights to end injustices for people of color.\" Fuller had previously modeled for clothing brand WLM Apparel, which uses the tagline \"White Lives Matter\" to promote the conservation of the [[white marlin]]. The tagline has been described by nongovernmental organizations such as the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] as \"a racist response to the civil rights movement Black Lives Matter\" and \"a [[neo-Nazi]] group that is growing into a movement as more and more [[white supremacist]] groups take up its slogans and tactics.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/juliareinstein/the-bachelor-cosmopolitan-cover-victoria-fuller-pulled|title=Cosmopolitan Pulled A \"Bachelor\" Contestant's Cover Because She Modeled \"White Lives Matter\" Merchandise|website=BuzzFeed News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\nDuring week eight, Weber's ex-girlfriend, Merissa Pence, made an appearance to warn Peter about contestant Victoria Fuller's reputation in her hometown of [[Virginia Beach, Virginia|Virginia Beach]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/why-peter-webers-ex-merissa-decided-to-go-on-the-bachelor/|title=Peter Weber\u2019s Ex Merissa Pence Explains Why She Went on \u2018The Bachelor\u2019|last=Longeretta|first=Emily|date=February 17, 2020|website=[[Us Weekly]]|access-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref> News outlets have also reported on Fuller being arrested for a [[Driving under the influence|DUI]] charge back in 2017 where she was sentenced to a year in jail. The sentence was suspended, and Fuller was given 24 months of probation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pagesix.com/2020/02/17/bachelor-contestant-victoria-fuller-previously-arrested-for-dui/|title=\u2018Bachelor\u2019 contestant Victoria Fuller previously arrested for DWI|authors=Jaclyn Hendricks, Chelsea Hirsch|date=February 17, 2020|website=[[New York Post|Page Six]]|access-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://abc.go.com/shows/the-bachelor}}\n\n{{The Bachelor}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bachelor 24, The}}\n[[Category:The Bachelor seasons|24]]\n[[Category:2020 American television seasons]]\n", "name_user": "Speditor215", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEpisodes:cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Bachelor_(season_24)"}
{"title_page": "Yellow-faced honeyeater", "text_new": "{{featured article}}\n{{use Australian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|Species of bird in the family Meliphagidae}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Yellow-faced honeyeater\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704052/0 |title=''Caligavis chrysops'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2018 |access-date=7 September 2019|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| image = Caligavis_chrysops_-_Lake_Parramatta_Reserve.jpg\n| genus = Caligavis\n| parent_authority =\n| species = chrysops\n| range_map           = YellowfacedHEmap.png\n| range_map_caption   = Yellow-faced honeyeater natural range<br>subsp. ''barroni'' olive<br>subsp. ''chrysops'' green<br>subsp. ''samueli'' blue\n| authority = ([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1801)\n| synonyms =\n* ''Sylvia chrysops'' <small>Latham, 1801</small>\n* ''Lichenostomus chrysops'' <small>(Latham, 1802)</small>\n* ''Melithreptus gilvicapillus'' <small>Vieillot, 1817</small>\n* ''Ptilotis trivirgata'' <small>[[George Robert Gray|G.R. Gray]], 1869</small>\n}}\n\nThe '''yellow-faced honeyeater''' (''Caligavis chrysops'') is a small to medium-sized bird in the [[honeyeater]] [[family (biology)|family]], Meliphagidae. It takes its common and scientific names from the distinctive yellow stripes on the sides of its head. Its loud, clear call often begins twenty or thirty minutes before dawn. It is widespread across eastern and southeastern Australia, in open [[sclerophyll]] forests from coastal dunes to high-altitude [[subalpine area]]s, and [[woodland]]s along creeks and rivers. Comparatively short-billed for a honeyeater, it is thought to have adapted to a diet of flies, spiders, and beetles, as well as nectar and pollen from the flowers of plants, such as ''[[Banksia]]'' and ''[[Grevillea]]'', and soft fruits. It catches insects in flight as well as [[Gleaning (birds)|gleaning]] them from the foliage of trees and shrubs.\n\nSome yellow-faced honeyeaters are sedentary, but hundreds of thousands [[bird migration|migrate]] northwards between March and May to spend the winter in southern [[Queensland]], and return in July and August to breed in southern [[New South Wales]] and [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]. They form [[Monogamy in animals|socially monogamous]] pairs and lay two or three eggs in a delicate [[cup nest|cup-shaped nest]]. The success rate can be low, and the pairs nest several times during the breeding season.\n\nHoneyeaters' preferred woodland habitat is vulnerable to the effects of land-clearing, grazing, and weeds. As it is common and widespread, the yellow-faced honeyeater is considered by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) to be of [[least concern]] for conservation. It is considered a pest in orchards in some areas.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe yellow-faced honeyeater was first [[species description|described]], and placed in the genus ''[[Typical warbler|Sylvia]]'', by ornithologist, [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]], in his 1801 work, ''Supplementum Indicis Ornithologici, sive Systematis Ornithologiae''.<ref name=latham01>{{cite book | last=Latham | first=John | author-link=John Latham (ornithologist) | year=1801 | title=Supplementum indicis ornithologici sive systematis ornithologiae | place=London | publisher=Leigh & Sotheby | language=Latin | page=liv | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33261428 }}</ref><ref name=Latham>{{cite journal | last = Schodde| first = Richard | authorlink = Richard Schodde |author2=Dickinson, Edward C. |author3=Steinheimer, Frank D. |author4=Bock, Walter J.  | title = The date of Latham's ''Supplementum Indicis Ornithologici'': 1801 or 1802? | journal = South Australian Ornithologist | volume = 35| issue = 8 | pages = 231\u2013235 | year = 2010| url=http://www.birdssa.asn.au/images/saopdfs/Volume35/2010V35P231.pdf }}</ref> French ornithologist, [[Louis Jean Pierre Vieillot]], described it as ''Melithreptus gilvicapillus'' in 1817, and English zoologist, [[George Robert Gray]], as ''Ptilotis trivirgata'' in 1869.<ref name=\"AFD\">{{cite web|url=https://biodiversity.org.au/afd/taxa/f27e5973-dc69-40d0-af23-ae1c49d6e0b3|title=Subspecies ''Caligavis chrysops chrysops'' (Latham, 1801)|author=Australian Biological Resources Study|date=13 October 2014|work=Australian Faunal Directory|publisher=Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts, Australian Government|accessdate=7 January 2017|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory}}</ref> The specific name ''chrysops'' is derived from the [[Ancient Greek]] words ''chrysos'' meaning 'gold' and ''prosopo'' meaning 'face', in reference to the stripe of yellow feathers.<ref name=fraser13>{{cite book|last1=Gray|first1=Jeannie|last2=Fraser|first2=Ian|title=Australian Bird Names: A Complete Guide|url=https://books.google.com/?id=W1TCqHVWQp0C&pg=PT199#v=onepage&q=Yellow-faced%20honeyeater%20&f=false|year=2013|publisher=Csiro Publishing|location=Collingwood, Victoria | isbn=978-0-643-10471-6|page=199}}</ref>\n\nThe yellow-faced honeyeater was classified in the genera ''[[Meliphaga]]'' and then ''[[Lichenostomus]]'' until 2011.<ref name=\"AFD\"/> Delineating the latter genus had been systematically contentious, and evaluations of relationships among honeyeaters in the genus, using dense [[taxon]] and [[nucleotide]] sampling, confirmed previous findings that ''Lichenostomus'' is not [[Monophyly|monophyletic]].<ref name =Gardener>{{cite journal| last = Gardner | first = J.L.  | last2 = Trueman |first2=J.W.H. |last3=Ebert|first3=D. |last4=Joseph |first4=L. |last5=Magrath|first5=R.D. | title = Phylogeny and evolution of the ''Meliphagoidea'', the largest radiation of Australian songbirds  | journal = Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume = 55 | issue =  3| pages = 1087\u20131102 | year = 2010 | issn = 1055-7903  | doi = 10.1016/j.ympev.2010.02.005\n| pmid = 20152917}}</ref> Five species have previously been described as comprising the ''Caligavis'' subgroup, but studies, using the [[Mitochondrial DNA|mitochondrial]] DNA, identified the yellow-faced honeyeater as most closely related to the [[black-throated honeyeater]] (''C. subfrenatus'') and the [[obscure honeyeater]] (''C. obscurus'') of New Guinea; they were, therefore, grouped into the genus ''[[Caligavis]]''. The [[bridled honeyeater]] (''B. frenatus'') and the [[Eungella honeyeater]] (''B. hindwoodi'') were sufficiently different to be placed in a separate genus as ''[[Bolemoreus]]''.<ref name =Nyan>{{cite journal| last = Ny\u00e1ri | first = \u00c1rp\u00e1d S. | last2 = Joseph |first2 = Leo | title = Systematic dismantlement of ''Lichenostomus'' improves the basis for understanding relationships within the honeyeaters (Meliphagidae) and the historical development of Australo-Papuan bird communities| journal = Emu | volume = 111| issue = 3| pages = 202\u2013211 | year = 2011 | doi = 10.1071/MU10047}}</ref> A 2017 genetic study, using both mitochondrial and nuclear DNA, found the ancestor of the yellow-faced honeyeater diverged from the common ancestor of the other two ''Caligavis'' species around seven million years ago.<ref name=\"Marki 2017\">{{cite journal|author=Marki, Petter Z.; J\u00f8nsson, Knud A., Irestedt, Martin; Nguyen, Jacqueline M.T.; Rahbek, Carsten; Fjelds\u00e5, Jon |date=2017|title=Supermatrix phylogeny and biogeography of the Australasian Meliphagides radiation (Aves: Passeriformes)|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=107|pages=516\u201329|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2016.12.021|pmid=28017855|hdl=10852/65203}}</ref>\n\nThere are three [[subspecies]] of the yellow-faced honeyeater, two of which were described by [[Gregory Mathews]] in 1912.<ref name=\"AFD2\">{{cite web|url=https://biodiversity.org.au/afd/taxa/ed4ff115-ea04-4261-848d-d9dcb4e2a04a|title=Subspecies ''Caligavis chrysops barroni'' (Mathews, 1912)|author=Australian Biological Resources Study|date=13 October 2014|work=Australian Faunal Directory|publisher=Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts, Australian Government|accessdate=15 February 2017|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory}}</ref><ref name=\"AFD3\">{{cite web|url=https://biodiversity.org.au/afd/taxa/e2bd6b72-6f6f-4d35-ad33-4536f6fefb64|title=Subspecies ''Caligavis chrysops samueli'' (Mathews, 1912)|author=Australian Biological Resources Study|date=13 October 2014|work=Australian Faunal Directory|publisher=Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts, Australian Government|accessdate=15 February 2017|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory}}</ref> There are only very slight differences between the nominate race and ''C. c. samueli'' found in the [[Mount Lofty Ranges]] in [[South Australia]], and ''C. c. barroni'' from the [[Clarke Range]] and the [[Atherton Tableland]] in [[Queensland]]. The latter race is described as \"poorly differentiated\" and \"possibly not worthy of recognition\" by the ''[[Handbook of the Birds of the World]]''.{{sfn|Higgins|Christidis|Ford|2008|p=597}}\n\nSurgeon-General to the [[First Fleet]], [[John White (surgeon)|John White]], caught a specimen in May 1788, calling it a yellow-faced flycatcher in his ''Journal of a Voyage to New South Wales'', which was published in 1790.<ref name=JournalOfAVoyage>{{cite book |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/47182712 |title=Journal of a Voyage to New South Wales with sixty-five plates of nondescript animals, birds, lizards, serpents, curious cones of trees and other natural productions |volume=1790 |author=White, John |work=|pages=161 |year=1790|publisher=Printed for J. Debrett }}</ref> Latham called it the black-cheeked warbler.<ref name=latham01/> [[John Gould]] called it the yellow-faced honeyeater in 1848,<ref>{{cite book | last=Gould | first=John | author-link=John Gould | year=1848 | title=The Birds of Australia | volume=Volume 4 | place=London | publisher=Self-published | at=Plate 45 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48702996 }}</ref> which has become its official name. It is also known as the yellow-gaped honeyeater, or the quitchup, in reference to its call.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=724}}\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Yellow-faced Honeyeater nov07.jpg|thumb|right|alt= Yellow-faced honeyeater with body partially turned towards the camera|A distinctive yellow stripe runs below the eye.]]\n\n===Appearance===\nThe yellow-faced honeyeater is a medium-small, greyish-brown bird that takes its common name from distinctive yellow stripes on the sides of the head.{{sfn|Officer|1965|p=50}} Yellow feathers form a narrow stripe above the [[Beak#Gape|gape]], which broadens and curves below the eye to end in a small white patch of feathers on the [[Covert feather#Ear coverts|ear coverts]]. Above the yellow stripe is a black eye stripe which is broken by a small yellow to off-white patch behind the eye, and below is another distinct black stripe running the length of the yellow line. The chin, throat, and breast are a pale greyish-brown, streaked with slightly darker grey, and the abdomen is light grey. The upper body is a dark greyish-brown to olive-brown. Olive-green outer edges on the [[Flight feather|remiges]] combine to form an olive panel on the folded wing. The bill is black and slightly down-curved, and the gape is cream. The legs and feet are grey-brown. The [[Iris (anatomy)|iris]] is a dusky blue in adult birds, and brown in juveniles. The juvenile is very similar to the adult, with slightly less streaking on the breast, an orange-brown tip on the bill, and a yellower gape; male and female birds are also similar, with the male being slightly larger (on average, {{convert|0.8|g|oz|abbr=on}} heavier); and in the field there are no visible differences between the subspecies. The yellow-faced honeyeater averages {{convert|15|-|17.5|cm|in}} in length, with a wingspan of {{convert|21.5|-|26|cm|in|abbr=on}}, and a weight of {{convert|12.5|-|20.5|g|oz}}, with an average of {{convert|17|g|oz|abbr=on}}).{{sfn|Higgins|Christidis|Ford|2008|p=597}}{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=724}}\n\n===Vocalizations===\nOne of the first birds heard in the morning, the yellow-faced honeyeater utters calls that are full and loud, and extremely varied. The male sings from a roost for up to an hour, beginning twenty or thirty minutes before dawn.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=724}} The song is a running series of cheerful notes sounding like ''chick-up, chick-up'', from which its common name of quitchup is derived.{{sfn|Officer|1965|p=50}} Counter-singing (repeating the first bird's song) by neighbouring birds is common. The territorial call, also given by opponents during fights, is a long ''preet'' with an upward inflection. The alarm call is a loud trilling whistle. Common calls, thought to be [[contact call]]s, are animated two-note calls variously described as ''terric, terric'', ''cr-rook, cr-rook'' or ''put-put, put-put''.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=724}}\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n[[File:Yellow-faced Honeyeater callistemon.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Honeyeater balancing on a bottlebrush flower|The yellow-faced honeyeater can be seen feeding on garden shrubs.]]\n\n===Habitat===\nAcross its range, the yellow-faced honeyeater is found in a variety of habitats\u2014in open [[sclerophyll]] forests from coastal dunes to high-altitude subalpine areas, and often in [[Riparian zone|riparian]] woodlands. It most commonly dwells in open forests dominated by spotted gum (''[[Corymbia maculata]]'') with [[ironbark]]s and [[stringybark]]s, such as narrow-leaved ironbark (''[[Eucalyptus crebra]]'') and silver-leaved ironbark ([[Eucalyptus melanophloia|''E. melanophloia'']]), with a light, shrubby [[understorey]], and less often in dry, open forests and [[woodland]]s dominated by ''[[Angophora]]'', ''[[Acacia]]'', ''[[Banksia]]'', ''[[Casuarina]]'' or ''[[Callitris]]'', or in high-altitude, tall, open forests of alpine ash (''[[Eucalyptus delegatensis]]'') and woodlands dominated by snow gum (''[[Eucalyptus pauciflora|E. pauciflora]]'') or white box (''[[Eucalyptus albens|E. albens]]''). It has been recorded in coastal [[heath]] when banksias are blooming, and among flowering [[mangrove]]s. It occupies areas infested with weeds, such as Scotch broom (''[[Cytisus scoparius]]'') and [[Blackberry|blackberries]], and in developed areas including orchards, parks and gardens, where it feeds on cultivated fruit and flowers. It can be found in forests regenerating after [[Bushfires in Australia|fire]] or [[logging]], though it is more common in mature forests.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=725}} Where it is found in woodland, it is usually woodland near forest or with an [[understory]] of sclerophyll plants.<ref name=\"Ford and Paton 76\">{{cite journal|last1=Ford|first1=Hugh A.|last2=Paton|first2=David C.|title=Resource partitioning and competition in honeyeaters of the genus ''Meliphaga''|journal=Australian Journal of Ecology|date=1976|volume=1|issue=4|pages=281\u2013287|doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.1976.tb01118.x}}</ref>\n\n===Range===\nThe yellow-faced honeyeater ranges across a broad arc generally along the coastline from near [[Cooktown]] in [[Far North Queensland]], and between a line from [[Charters Towers]] south to [[Albury]] and the coast, and then west to the [[Fleurieu Peninsula]] and the Mount Lofty Ranges in South Australia. Population densities have been recorded from 0.01 birds per hectare (2.5 acres) near [[Armidale]] in New South Wales to 7.8 birds per hectare at [[Tarnagulla, Victoria]]. During the winter months of June and July, numbers are generally lower in Victoria and higher in Queensland, following their northward migration.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=728}}\n\n===Migration===\nThere are resident populations of the yellow-faced honeyeater throughout its range, but it is for the most part a [[season]]al, [[Latitude|latitudinal]], daytime migrant. During the autumn (March to May), it migrates north along the highlands and coastal fringe of eastern Australia to southern Queensland, to return in the spring (August to October) of the same year.<ref name =Clarke>{{cite journal|title=The social organization and breeding behaviour of the Yellow-faced Honeyeater ''Lichenostomus chrysops''\u2013 a migratory passerine from the Southern Hemisphere|journal=Ibis|year=2003| first=Michael |last=Clarke |last2=Schipper |first2=Clinton |last3=Boulton |first3=Rebecca |last4=Ewen |first4=John |volume=145|issue=4|pages=611\u2013623|doi= 10.1046/j.1474-919X.2003.00203.x}}</ref> The birds commonly move in flocks of 10 to 100 birds, but occasionally in larger groups of 1,000 or more. The groups can include other species, such as the [[white-naped honeyeater]], [[fuscous honeyeater]], [[noisy friarbird]], and [[silvereye]]. They move in successive flocks at a rate of up to several thousand birds an hour.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=727}} Over 100,000 birds were recorded passing Hastings Point in New South Wales over the course of a single day in May 1965.<ref name = Liddy>{{cite journal  | last = Liddy  | first = John | title = Autumnal migration of the Yellow-faced Honeyeater  | journal = Emu  | volume = 66  | issue = 2  | pages = 87\u2013103 | year = 1966 | doi=10.1080/01584197.1966.11797179}}</ref> The species is able to detect [[Earth's magnetic field|geomagnetic fields]], and uses them to navigate while migrating.<ref name=Munro>{{cite journal|journal=Journal of Experimental Biology|volume= 181|pages=233\u2013244|year=1993|title=Clock-shift experiments with migratory Yellow-faced Honeyeaters, ''Lichenostomus chrysops'' (Meliphagidae), an Australian day-migrating bird|url=http://jeb.biologists.org/content/181/1/233.short |last= Munro|first= Ursula |author2=Wiltschko, Roswitha }}</ref> Experiments, where the vertical component of the [[magnetic field]] was reversed, indicate that the magnetic compass of the yellow-faced honeyeater is based on the inclination of the [[Magnet|field lines]] and not on [[Magnet|polarity]], meaning they distinguish between the direction of the equator and the South Pole, rather than north and south.<ref name =Munro2>{{cite journal|title=Magnetic compass orientation in the yellow-faced honeyeater, ''Lichenostomus chrysops'', a day migrating bird from Australia|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology| year=1993| first=Ursula|last=Munro| last2= Wiltschko |first2=Wolfgang |volume=32|issue=2|pages=141\u2013145|doi= 10.1007/BF00164047 }}</ref> Their flight is in one general direction, but is not in a straight line, as the flocks stay in vegetated areas, negotiate gaps in the mountain ranges, and detour around cities.<ref name=Wilson>{{cite journal | last = Wilson | first = S.J.| title = Mist netting migrating Yellow-faced Honeyeaters| journal = The Australian Bird Bander | volume = 1| pages = 53\u201359 | year = 1963 | issn = 0004-8747}}</ref>\n\nThe migration of many birds in Australia, including honeyeaters, has generally been described as occurring mainly in response to external environmental stimuli, such as food availability or an influx of water.<ref name=Keast>{{cite journal | last = Keast | first = A.| title = Seasonal movement in the Australian honeyeaters (Meliphagidae) and their ecological significance| journal = Emu| volume = 67| issue=2| pages = 159\u2013209 | year = 1968 | doi =10.1071/MU967159 }}</ref> The yellow-faced honeyeater has been found to have a broad range of characteristics that are more often associated with Northern Hemisphere migrants. These are an annual cycle of migratory restlessness, seasonally appropriate orientation based on magnetic, solar and polarised light cues, and a migration program based on the magnetic inclination compass.<ref name=migration>{{Cite book| first = Ursula| last = Munro| editor-last = Adams | editor-first = N.J. | editor2-last = Slotow | editor2-first = R.H. | contribution = Adaptations to a migratory lifestyle: An Australian perspective | title = Proceedings of the 22nd International Ornithological Congress | year = 1999 | pages = 956\u2013978 | place = Johannesburg   | publisher = BirdLife South Africa}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour==\n[[File:Yellow-faced Honeyeater lambertia.jpg|thumb|Piercing the base of a mountain devil (''Lambertia formosa'') flower to feed on nectar]]\nThe yellow-faced honeyeater is usually seen singly, in pairs or in small family groups, when not migrating.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=724}} They forage as individuals, as pairs or as small groups of up to ten birds, and during migration in larger groups. They sometimes feed in large, [[mixed-species foraging flock | mixed-species, foraging flock]]s, composed predominately of insectivorous birds.{{sfn|Higgins|Christidis|Ford|2008|p=597}}\n\n===Feeding===\nComparatively short-billed for a honeyeater, the yellow-faced honeyeater is thought to have adapted to a mixed diet.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=730}} Its diet consists of [[nectar]], [[pollen]], fruit, seeds, [[Honeydew (secretion)|honeydew]], and insects. It is arboreal, foraging primarily among the foliage and flowers of trees, shrubs, and [[mistletoe]]s, less often on branches and tree-trunk, and rarely on the ground.<ref name=Bounds>{{cite journal| last = Bounds| first = Jenny| title = Lone Fuscous and Yellow-faced Honeyeaters keeping company| journal = Canberra Bird Notes | volume = 21| issue = 1| page = 14 | year = 1996 | issn = 0314-8211}}</ref> Yellow-faced honeyeaters feed on nectar around 40% of the time, and on insects around 60% of the time.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=730}} The yellow-faced honeyeater feeds on insects by [[Gleaning (birds)|gleaning]], [[Hawking (birds)|sallying]], catching in flight, or probing in bark crevices. The insects eaten are primarily [[Diptera]] (flies, mosquitoes, maggots, gnats, and midges), [[beetle]]s, and [[spider]]s.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=731}} A study of the pollen on the bills and foreheads of captured birds found that 70% carried pollen from silver banksia (''[[Banksia marginata]]''), 61% from heath-leaved banksia (''[[Banksia ericifolia]]''), and 22% carried pollen from other plants in the area including fern-leaved banksia (''[[Banksia oblongifolia]]''), mountain devil (''[[Lambertia formosa]]''), and green spider-flower (''[[Grevillea mucronulata]]'').\n\nIn April and May, before the autumn migration, the yellow-faced honeyeater increases its nectar consumption, which increases its body mass. The average body mass in late autumn of {{convert|17.5|g|oz}} is 13% higher than the average recorded between January and April, and the yellow-faced honeyeater begins the migration with healthy fat reserves.{{sfn|Munro|2003|p=148}}\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Yellow-faced-honeyeater.jpg|thumb|alt=A yellow-faced honeyeater feeding its chicks in a nest in a rose bush| Three chicks are raised in a flimsy nest in a garden shrub.]]\nThe yellow-faced honeyeater breeds in [[Monogamy in animals|monogamous]] pairs in a breeding season that extends from July to March, with migrating birds nesting later than sedentary birds.<ref name=\"Clarke\"/> They nest solitarily in all-purpose [[Territory (animal)|territories]] that both parents defend against conspecifics and other species including [[Acanthiza|thornbills]], [[spinebill]]s and silvereyes, although the male is involved in more aggressive interactions than the female.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=732}} Within a breeding season, females lay two or three clutches of eggs, re-nesting with the same partner in the same territory. [[Bird ringing|Banded]] birds have been identified in the same territory for periods of up to five years.<ref name=\"Clarke\" />\n\nThe nest is built in the understorey shrubs, relatively close to the ground. Nests have been recorded in prickly coprosma (''[[Coprosma quadrifida]]''), ''[[Cassinia]]'', tea-trees (''[[Melaleuca]]''), [[eucalypt]]s and [[acacia]]s, as well as in garden shrubs.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=733}} The nest is a fragile, cup-shaped structure, swollen at the sides and narrower at the rim. The female builds the nest, but is often accompanied by the male as she gathers nesting material. Most nests are built of greenish material, which varies with the location; in coastal areas, grass is the primary material; in mountain forests, the nest is often covered with moss.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=734}} One bird was recorded repeatedly flying between the nest and a [[koala]] {{convert|36|m|ft}} away and plucking the long hair near its ears to incorporate in the nest.<ref name=Cody>{{cite journal| last = Cody | first = M.L. | title = Honeyeater plucks koala for nest material | journal = Emu | volume = 91 | issue = 2 | pages = 125\u2013126 | year = 1991 | doi = 10.1071/MU9910125}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.audubon.org/news/honeyeaters-steal-fur-sleeping-koalas-their-nests|title=Honeyeaters Steal Fur from Sleeping Koalas for Their Nests|date=2017-08-23|website=Audubon|language=en|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref> The nests are very fine, with the eggs visible through the gauze-like walls, and they sometimes fall apart. They have been known to disintegrate with eggs and nestlings falling through the bottom.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=734}}\n\nThe female undertakes the [[avian incubation|incubation]] alone.<ref name=\"Clarke\"/> Eggs are oval, approximately {{convert|21|mm|in}} long and {{convert|14|mm|in}} wide, and pinkish white in colour with spots and blotches of dark reddish-brown.{{sfn|Beruldsen|1980|p=371}} The [[clutch (eggs)|clutch]] size varies from one to three eggs, and eggs take around two weeks to hatch. Upon hatching, both parents feed the nestlings and remove [[Feces|faecal pellets]]. The chicks [[fledge]] after thirteen days, and leave the parental territory after a further two weeks. The success rate can be as low as 16% of eggs developing into fledged young, with nest failure, hot weather, heavy rain, human activity (including fungicide spraying and nest damage), egg destruction by [[brood parasite]]s, and [[predation]] by [[Pseudonaja|brown snakes]], cats, and [[currawong]]s, all recorded as contributing to brood failure.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=735}} Among the species that parasitize the nests of yellow-faced honeyeaters are [[fan-tailed cuckoo]]s, [[brush cuckoo]]s, [[pallid cuckoo]]s, [[shining bronze-cuckoo]]s, and [[Horsfield's bronze-cuckoo]]s.{{sfn|Higgins|Christidis|Ford|2008|p=597}} The yellow-faced honeyeater promptly nests again after both successful and failed breeding attempts.<ref name=Boulton>{{cite journal| last = Boulton | first = R.L| last2 = Cassey |first2=P. |last3=Schipper |first3=C. |last4=Clarke |first4=M.F. | title = Nest site selection by Yellow-faced Honeyeaters ''Lichenostomus chrysops'' | journal = Journal of Avian Biology | volume = 34 | pages = 267\u2013274  | year = 2003 | issn = 0908-8857| doi = 10.1034/j.1600-048X.2003.03062.x| issue = 3}}</ref>\n\nA paternity analysis of yellow-faced honeyeater nestlings found that 10 of 18 nestlings were fathered by the male of the nesting pair, with clear evidence for extra-pair paternity in the case of the remaining 44%. This conflicts with the usual pattern, where genetic [[monogamy]] is linked to the characteristics of strong social pairing, essential paternal contributions to brood-rearing, and to sexual [[Monomorphism (biology)|monomorphism]];<ref name= \"Ewen\">{{cite journal |author1=Ewen, John G. |author2=Ciborowski, Kate L. |author3=Clarke, Rohan H. |author4=Boulton, Rebecca L. |author5=Clarke, Michael F. | year = 2008| title = Evidence of extra-pair paternity in two socially monogamous Australian passerines: the Crescent Honeyeater and the Yellow-faced Honeyeater | journal = Emu | volume =108| pages =133\u2013137 | doi =10.1071/MU07040 |issue= 2}}</ref> characteristics that are exhibited by the [[yellow honeyeater]], for example.\n\n==Conservation status==\nSeveral [[Parasitism|ectoparasites]], which can affect survival and reproductive fitness, have been found on the yellow-faced honeyeater: the mites, [[Rhinonyssidae|''Ptilonyssus meliphagae'']] and ''P. thymanzae'', and ''[[Ixodes]]'' species ticks.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=1262}}\n\nIn general, honeyeaters require extensive [[Wildlife corridor|corridors]] of mature trees along their migratory routes, and flowering woodlands for nesting, so they are vulnerable to the effects of land-clearing, grazing and weed infestation. The woodland habitat they prefer is considered an endangered ecological community. As it is common and widespread, the yellow-faced honeyeater is considered by the [[IUCN]] to be of [[least concern]] for conservation.<ref name=IUCN/> A field experiment to determine whether yellow-faced honeyeater nests were less successful in fragmented habitats found that nests closer to forest margins actually had a higher success rate than those deeper in the forest. However, the yellow-faced honeyeater tends to nest away from the edge of forest remnants; experiments with natural and artificial nests at varying distances from the open areas showed no increase in the number of avian predators at the forest edge. The results of the field experiment did not support the \"[[ecological trap]]\" and \"predator influx\" theories, and contribute to a belief that [[Habitat fragmentation|fragmented habitats]] may not be as problematic as previously thought.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Do yellow-faced honeyeater (''Lichenostomus chrysops'') nests experience higher predation at forest edges? |last1=Boulton | first1=R.L. | last2=Clarke | first2=M.F. | journal =Wildlife Research | year= 2003 |volume=30| issue=2| pages=119\u2013125 | doi=10.1071/WR02055}}</ref><!-- cites prev 3 sentences --> In some areas, the species is considered a pest because of its intrusion into orchards and urban gardens, where it damages fruit.{{sfn|Officer|1965|p=50}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book |last=Beruldsen |first=Gordon |authorlink=Gordon Beruldsen |year=1980 |title=A Field Guide to Nests and Eggs of Australian Birds |location=Adelaide, S.A. |publisher=Rigby |isbn=978-0-7270-1202-9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Higgins |first=Peter |first2=J. M. |last2=Peter |last3=Steele |first3=W. K. |year=2001 |contribution=''Lichenostomus chrysops'' Yellow-faced Honeyeater |title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds Volume 5: Tyrant-flycatchers to Chats |location=Melbourne, Vic. |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=724\u2013740 |isbn=978-0-19-553071-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Higgins |first=Peter |last2=Christidis |first2=Les |last3=Ford |first3=Hugh |year=2008 |contribution=Family Meliphagidae (Honeyeaters) |editor-last=Josep |editor-first=del Hoyo |editor2-last=Andrew |editor2-first=Elliott |editor3-last=David |editor3-first=Christie |title=Handbook of the Birds of the World Volume 13: Penduline-tits to Shrikes |title-link=Handbook of the Birds of the World |place=Barcelona |publisher=Lynx Edicions |pages=597\u2013598 |isbn=978-84-96553-45-3  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |first=Ursula |last=Munro |year=2003 |contribution=Life History and Ecophysical Adaptations to Migration in Australian Birds |editor-last=Berthold |editor-first=Peter |editor2-last=Gwinner |editor2-first=Eberhard |editor3-last=Sonnenschein |editor3-first=E. |title=Avian Migration |place=New York |publisher=Springer-Verlag |pages=141\u2013154 |isbn=978-3-540-43408-5  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Officer |first=Hugh R. |year=1965 |title=Australian Honeyeaters |location=Melbourne, Vic. |publisher=The Bird Observers Club, Melbourne |isbn=978-0-909711-03-0 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Caligavis chrysops}}\n{{Wikispecies|Caligavis chrysops}}\n\n* [http://www.xeno-canto.org/species/Caligavis-chrysops Xeno-canto: audio recordings of the yellow-faced honeyeater]\n* {{cite web | title=Yellow-faced Honeyeaters spring migration: Podcast | publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation: Radio National | url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/breakfast/stories/2011/3319096.htm | date=16 September 2011 }}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27075233}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:honeyeater, yellow-faced}}\n[[Category:Caligavis|yellow-faced honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Birds of Queensland]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1801|yellow-faced honeyeater]]\n", "text_old": "{{featured article}}\n{{use Australian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|Species of bird in the family Meliphagidae}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Yellow-faced honeyeater\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704052/0 |title=''Caligavis chrysops'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2018 |access-date=7 September 2019|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| image = Caligavis_chrysops_-_Lake_Parramatta_Reserve.jpg\n| genus = Caligavis\n| parent_authority =\n| species = chrysops\n| range_map           = YellowfacedHEmap.png\n| range_map_caption   = Yellow-faced honeyeater natural range<br>subsp. ''barroni'' olive<br>subsp. ''chrysops'' green<br>subsp. ''samueli'' blue\n| authority = ([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1801)\n| synonyms =\n* ''Sylvia chrysops'' <small>Latham, 1801</small>\n* ''Lichenostomus chrysops'' <small>(Latham, 1802)</small>\n* ''Melithreptus gilvicapillus'' <small>Vieillot, 1817</small>\n* ''Ptilotis trivirgata'' <small>[[George Robert Gray|G.R. Gray]], 1869</small>\n}}\n\nThe '''yellow-faced honeyeater''' (''Caligavis chrysops'') is a small to medium-sized bird in the [[honeyeater]] [[family (biology)|family]], Meliphagidae. It takes its common and scientific names from the distinctive yellow stripes on the sides of its head. Its loud, clear call often begins twenty or thirty minutes before dawn. It is widespread across eastern and southeastern Australia, in open [[sclerophyll]] forests from coastal dunes to high-altitude [[subalpine area]]s, and [[woodland]]s along creeks and rivers. Comparatively short-billed for a honeyeater, it is thought to have adapted to a diet of flies, spiders, and beetles, as well as nectar and pollen from the flowers of plants, such as ''[[Banksia]]'' and ''[[Grevillea]]'', and soft fruits. It catches insects in flight as well as [[Gleaning (birds)|gleaning]] them from the foliage of trees and shrubs.\n\nSome yellow-faced honeyeaters are sedentary, but hundreds of thousands [[bird migration|migrate]] northwards between March and May to spend the winter in southern [[Queensland]], and return in July and August to breed in southern [[New South Wales]] and [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]. They form [[Monogamy in animals|socially monogamous]] pairs and lay two or three eggs in a delicate [[cup nest|cup-shaped nest]]. The success rate can be low, and the pairs nest several times during the breeding season.\n\nHoneyeaters' preferred woodland habitat is vulnerable to the effects of land-clearing, grazing, and weeds. As it is common and widespread, the yellow-faced honeyeater is considered by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) to be of [[least concern]] for conservation. It is considered a pest in orchards in some areas.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe yellow-faced honeyeater was first [[species description|described]], and placed in the genus ''[[Typical warbler|Sylvia]]'', by ornithologist, [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]], in his 1801 work, ''Supplementum Indicis Ornithologici, sive Systematis Ornithologiae''.<ref name=latham01>{{cite book | last=Latham | first=John | author-link=John Latham (ornithologist) | year=1801 | title=Supplementum indicis ornithologici sive systematis ornithologiae | place=London | publisher=Leigh & Sotheby | language=Latin | page=liv | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33261428 }}</ref><ref name=Latham>{{cite journal | last = Schodde| first = Richard | authorlink = Richard Schodde |author2=Dickinson, Edward C. |author3=Steinheimer, Frank D. |author4=Bock, Walter J.  | title = The date of Latham's ''Supplementum Indicis Ornithologici'': 1801 or 1802? | journal = South Australian Ornithologist | volume = 35| issue = 8 | pages = 231\u2013235 | year = 2010| url=http://www.birdssa.asn.au/images/saopdfs/Volume35/2010V35P231.pdf }}</ref> French ornithologist, [[Louis Jean Pierre Vieillot]], described it as ''Melithreptus gilvicapillus'' in 1817, and English zoologist, [[George Robert Gray]], as ''Ptilotis trivirgata'' in 1869.<ref name=\"AFD\">{{cite web|url=https://biodiversity.org.au/afd/taxa/f27e5973-dc69-40d0-af23-ae1c49d6e0b3|title=Subspecies ''Caligavis chrysops chrysops'' (Latham, 1801)|author=Australian Biological Resources Study|date=13 October 2014|work=Australian Faunal Directory|publisher=Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts, Australian Government|accessdate=7 January 2017|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory}}</ref> The specific name ''chrysops'' is derived from the [[Ancient Greek]] words ''chrysos'' meaning 'gold' and ''prosopo'' meaning 'face', in reference to the stripe of yellow feathers.<ref name=fraser13>{{cite book|last1=Gray|first1=Jeannie|last2=Fraser|first2=Ian|title=Australian Bird Names: A Complete Guide|url=https://books.google.com/?id=W1TCqHVWQp0C&pg=PT199#v=onepage&q=Yellow-faced%20honeyeater%20&f=false|year=2013|publisher=Csiro Publishing|location=Collingwood, Victoria | isbn=978-0-643-10471-6|page=199}}</ref>\n\nThe yellow-faced honeyeater was classified in the genera ''[[Meliphaga]]'' and then ''[[Lichenostomus]]'' until 2011.<ref name=\"AFD\"/> Delineating the latter genus had been systematically contentious, and evaluations of relationships among honeyeaters in the genus, using dense [[taxon]] and [[nucleotide]] sampling, confirmed previous findings that ''Lichenostomus'' is not [[Monophyly|monophyletic]].<ref name =Gardener>{{cite journal| last = Gardner | first = J.L.  | last2 = Trueman |first2=J.W.H. |last3=Ebert|first3=D. |last4=Joseph |first4=L. |last5=Magrath|first5=R.D. | title = Phylogeny and evolution of the ''Meliphagoidea'', the largest radiation of Australian songbirds  | journal = Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume = 55 | issue =  3| pages = 1087\u20131102 | year = 2010 | issn = 1055-7903  | doi = 10.1016/j.ympev.2010.02.005\n| pmid = 20152917}}</ref> Five species have previously been described as comprising the ''Caligavis'' subgroup, but studies, using the [[Mitochondrial DNA|mitochondrial]] DNA, identified the yellow-faced honeyeater as most closely related to the [[black-throated honeyeater]] (''C. subfrenatus'') and the [[obscure honeyeater]] (''C. obscurus'') of New Guinea; they were, therefore, grouped into the genus ''[[Caligavis]]''. The [[bridled honeyeater]] (''B. frenatus'') and the [[Eungella honeyeater]] (''B. hindwoodi'') were sufficiently different to be placed in a separate genus as ''[[Bolemoreus]]''.<ref name =Nyan>{{cite journal| last = Ny\u00e1ri | first = \u00c1rp\u00e1d S. | last2 = Joseph |first2 = Leo | title = Systematic dismantlement of ''Lichenostomus'' improves the basis for understanding relationships within the honeyeaters (Meliphagidae) and the historical development of Australo-Papuan bird communities| journal = Emu | volume = 111| issue = 3| pages = 202\u2013211 | year = 2011 | doi = 10.1071/MU10047}}</ref> A 2017 genetic study, using both mitochondrial and nuclear DNA, found the ancestor of the yellow-faced honeyeater diverged from the common ancestor of the other two ''Caligavis'' species around seven million years ago.<ref name=\"Marki 2017\">{{cite journal|author=Marki, Petter Z.; J\u00f8nsson, Knud A., Irestedt, Martin; Nguyen, Jacqueline M.T.; Rahbek, Carsten; Fjelds\u00e5, Jon |date=2017|title=Supermatrix phylogeny and biogeography of the Australasian Meliphagides radiation (Aves: Passeriformes)|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=107|pages=516\u201329|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2016.12.021|pmid=28017855|hdl=10852/65203}}</ref>\n\nThere are three [[subspecies]] of the yellow-faced honeyeater, two of which were described by [[Gregory Mathews]] in 1912.<ref name=\"AFD2\">{{cite web|url=https://biodiversity.org.au/afd/taxa/ed4ff115-ea04-4261-848d-d9dcb4e2a04a|title=Subspecies ''Caligavis chrysops barroni'' (Mathews, 1912)|author=Australian Biological Resources Study|date=13 October 2014|work=Australian Faunal Directory|publisher=Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts, Australian Government|accessdate=15 February 2017|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory}}</ref><ref name=\"AFD3\">{{cite web|url=https://biodiversity.org.au/afd/taxa/e2bd6b72-6f6f-4d35-ad33-4536f6fefb64|title=Subspecies ''Caligavis chrysops samueli'' (Mathews, 1912)|author=Australian Biological Resources Study|date=13 October 2014|work=Australian Faunal Directory|publisher=Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts, Australian Government|accessdate=15 February 2017|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory}}</ref> There are only very slight differences between the nominate race and ''C. c. samueli'' found in the [[Mount Lofty Ranges]] in [[South Australia]], and ''C. c. barroni'' from the [[Clarke Range]] and the [[Atherton Tableland]] in [[Queensland]]. The latter race is described as \"poorly differentiated\" and \"possibly not worthy of recognition\" by the ''[[Handbook of the Birds of the World]]''.{{sfn|Higgins|Christidis|Ford|2008|p=597}}\n\nSurgeon-General to the [[First Fleet]], [[John White (surgeon)|John White]], caught a specimen in May 1788, calling it a yellow-faced flycatcher in his ''Journal of a Voyage to New South Wales'', which was published in 1790.<ref name=JournalOfAVoyage>{{cite book |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/47182712 |title=Journal of a Voyage to New South Wales with sixty-five plates of nondescript animals, birds, lizards, serpents, curious cones of trees and other natural productions |volume=1790 |author=White, John |work=|pages=161 |year=1790|publisher=Printed for J. Debrett }}</ref> Latham called it the black-cheeked warbler.<ref name=latham01/> [[John Gould]] called it the yellow-faced honeyeater in 1848,<ref>{{cite book | last=Gould | first=John | author-link=John Gould | year=1848 | title=The Birds of Australia | volume=Volume 4 | place=London | publisher=Self-published | at=Plate 45 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48702996 }}</ref> which has become its official name. It is also known as the yellow-gaped honeyeater, or the quitchup, in reference to its call.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=724}}\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Yellow-faced Honeyeater nov07.jpg|thumb|right|alt= Yellow-faced honeyeater with body partially turned towards the camera|A distinctive yellow stripe runs below the eye.]]\n\n===Appearance===\nThe yellow-faced honeyeater is a medium-small, greyish-brown bird that takes its common name from distinctive yellow stripes on the sides of the head.{{sfn|Officer|1965|p=50}} Yellow feathers form a narrow stripe above the [[Beak#Gape|gape]], which broadens and curves below the eye to end in a small white patch of feathers on the [[Covert feather#Ear coverts|ear coverts]]. Above the yellow stripe is a black eye stripe which is broken by a small yellow to off-white patch behind the eye, and below is another distinct black stripe running the length of the yellow line. The chin, throat, and breast are a pale greyish-brown, streaked with slightly darker grey, and the abdomen is light grey. The upper body is a dark greyish-brown to olive-brown. Olive-green outer edges on the [[Flight feather|remiges]] combine to form an olive panel on the folded wing. The bill is black and slightly down-curved, and the gape is cream. The legs and feet are grey-brown. The [[Iris (anatomy)|iris]] is a dusky blue in adult birds, and brown in juveniles. The juvenile is very similar to the adult, with slightly less streaking on the breast, an orange-brown tip on the bill, and a yellower gape; male and female birds are also similar, with the male being slightly larger (on average, {{convert|0.8|g|oz|abbr=on}} heavier); and in the field there are no visible differences between the subspecies. The yellow-faced honeyeater averages {{convert|15|-|17.5|cm|in}} in length, with a wingspan of {{convert|21.5|-|26|cm|in|abbr=on}}, and a weight of {{convert|12.5|-|20.5|g|oz}}, with an average of {{convert|17|g|oz|abbr=on}}).{{sfn|Higgins|Christidis|Ford|2008|p=597}}{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=724}}\n\n===Vocalizations===\nOne of the first birds heard in the morning, the yellow-faced honeyeater utters calls that are full and loud, and extremely varied. The male sings from a roost for up to an hour, beginning twenty or thirty minutes before dawn.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=724}} The song is a running series of cheerful notes sounding like ''chick-up, chick-up'', from which its common name of quitchup is derived.{{sfn|Officer|1965|p=50}} Counter-singing (repeating the first bird's song) by neighbouring birds is common. The territorial call, also given by opponents during fights, is a long ''preet'' with an upward inflection. The alarm call is a loud trilling whistle. Common calls, thought to be [[contact call]]s, are animated two-note calls variously described as ''terric, terric'', ''cr-rook, cr-rook'' or ''put-put, put-put''.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=724}}\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n[[File:Yellow-faced Honeyeater callistemon.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Honeyeater balancing on a bottlebrush flower|The yellow-faced honeyeater can be seen feeding on garden shrubs.]]\n\n===Habitat===\nAcross its range, the yellow-faced honeyeater is found in a variety of habitats\u2014in open [[sclerophyll]] forests from coastal dunes to high-altitude subalpine areas, and often in [[Riparian zone|riparian]] woodlands. It most commonly dwells in open forests dominated by spotted gum (''[[Corymbia maculata]]'') with [[ironbark]]s and [[stringybark]]s, such as narrow-leaved ironbark (''[[Eucalyptus crebra]]'') and silver-leaved ironbark ([[Eucalyptus melanophloia|''E. melanophloia'']]), with a light, shrubby [[understorey]], and less often in dry, open forests and [[woodland]]s dominated by ''[[Angophora]]'', ''[[Acacia]]'', ''[[Banksia]]'', ''[[Casuarina]]'' or ''[[Callitris]]'', or in high-altitude, tall, open forests of alpine ash (''[[Eucalyptus delegatensis]]'') and woodlands dominated by snow gum (''[[Eucalyptus pauciflora|E. pauciflora]]'') or white box (''[[Eucalyptus albens|E. albens]]''). It has been recorded in coastal [[heath]] when banksias are blooming, and among flowering [[mangrove]]s. It occupies areas infested with weeds, such as Scotch broom (''[[Cytisus scoparius]]'') and [[Blackberry|blackberries]], and in developed areas including orchards, parks and gardens, where it feeds on cultivated fruit and flowers. It can be found in forests regenerating after [[Bushfires in Australia|fire]] or [[logging]], though it is more common in mature forests.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=725}} Where it is found in woodland, it is usually woodland near forest or with an [[understory]] of sclerophyll plants.<ref name=\"Ford and Paton 76\">{{cite journal|last1=Ford|first1=Hugh A.|last2=Paton|first2=David C.|title=Resource partitioning and competition in honeyeaters of the genus ''Meliphaga''|journal=Australian Journal of Ecology|date=1976|volume=1|issue=4|pages=281\u2013287|doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.1976.tb01118.x}}</ref>\n\n===Range===\nThe yellow-faced honeyeater ranges across a broad arc generally along the coastline from near [[Cooktown]] in [[Far North Queensland]], and between a line from [[Charters Towers]] south to [[Albury]] and the coast, and then west to the [[Fleurieu Peninsula]] and the Mount Lofty Ranges in South Australia. Population densities have been recorded from 0.01 birds per hectare (2.5 acres) near [[Armidale]] in New South Wales to 7.8 birds per hectare at [[Tarnagulla, Victoria]]. During the winter months of June and July, numbers are generally lower in Victoria and higher in Queensland, following their northward migration.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=728}}\n\n===Migration===\nThere are resident populations of the yellow-faced honeyeater throughout its range, but it is for the most part a [[season]]al, [[Latitude|latitudinal]], daytime migrant. During the autumn (March to May), it migrates north along the highlands and coastal fringe of eastern Australia to southern Queensland, to return in the spring (August to October) of the same year.<ref name =Clarke>{{cite journal|title=The social organization and breeding behaviour of the Yellow-faced Honeyeater ''Lichenostomus chrysops''\u2013 a migratory passerine from the Southern Hemisphere|journal=Ibis|year=2003| first=Michael |last=Clarke |last2=Schipper |first2=Clinton |last3=Boulton |first3=Rebecca |last4=Ewen |first4=John |volume=145|issue=4|pages=611\u2013623|doi= 10.1046/j.1474-919X.2003.00203.x}}</ref> The birds commonly move in flocks of 10 to 100 birds, but occasionally in larger groups of 1,000 or more. The groups can include other species, such as the [[white-naped honeyeater]], [[fuscous honeyeater]], [[noisy friarbird]], and [[silvereye]]. They move in successive flocks at a rate of up to several thousand birds an hour.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=727}} Over 100,000 birds were recorded passing Hastings Point in New South Wales over the course of a single day in May 1965.<ref name = Liddy>{{cite journal  | last = Liddy  | first = John | title = Autumnal migration of the Yellow-faced Honeyeater  | journal = Emu  | volume = 66  | issue = 2  | pages = 87\u2013103 | year = 1966 | doi=10.1080/01584197.1966.11797179}}</ref> The species is able to detect [[Earth's magnetic field|geomagnetic fields]], and uses them to navigate while migrating.<ref name=Munro>{{cite journal|journal=Journal of Experimental Biology|volume= 181|pages=233\u2013244|year=1993|title=Clock-shift experiments with migratory Yellow-faced Honeyeaters, ''Lichenostomus chrysops'' (Meliphagidae), an Australian day-migrating bird|url=http://jeb.biologists.org/content/181/1/233.short |last= Munro|first= Ursula |author2=Wiltschko, Roswitha }}</ref> Experiments, where the vertical component of the [[magnetic field]] was reversed, indicate that the magnetic compass of the yellow-faced honeyeater is based on the inclination of the [[Magnet|field lines]] and not on [[Magnet|polarity]], meaning they distinguish between the direction of the equator and the South Pole, rather than north and south.<ref name =Munro2>{{cite journal|title=Magnetic compass orientation in the yellow-faced honeyeater, ''Lichenostomus chrysops'', a day migrating bird from Australia|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology| year=1993| first=Ursula|last=Munro| last2= Wiltschko |first2=Wolfgang |volume=32|issue=2|pages=141\u2013145|doi= 10.1007/BF00164047 }}</ref> Their flight is in one general direction, but is not in a straight line, as the flocks stay in vegetated areas, negotiate gaps in the mountain ranges, and detour around cities.<ref name=Wilson>{{cite journal | last = Wilson | first = S.J.| title = Mist netting migrating Yellow-faced Honeyeaters| journal = The Australian Bird Bander | volume = 1| pages = 53\u201359 | year = 1963 | issn = 0004-8747}}</ref>\n\nThe migration of many birds in Australia, including honeyeaters, has generally been described as occurring mainly in response to external environmental stimuli, such as food availability or an influx of water.<ref name=Keast>{{cite journal | last = Keast | first = A.| title = Seasonal movement in the Australian honeyeaters (Meliphagidae) and their ecological significance| journal = Emu| volume = 67| issue=2| pages = 159\u2013209 | year = 1968 | doi =10.1071/MU967159 }}</ref> The yellow-faced honeyeater has been found to have a broad range of characteristics that are more often associated with Northern Hemisphere migrants. These are an annual cycle of migratory restlessness, seasonally appropriate orientation based on magnetic, solar and polarised light cues, and a migration program based on the magnetic inclination compass.<ref name=migration>{{Cite book| first = Ursula| last = Munro| editor-last = Adams | editor-first = N.J. | editor2-last = Slotow | editor2-first = R.H. | contribution = Adaptations to a migratory lifestyle: An Australian perspective | title = Proceedings of the 22nd International Ornithological Congress | year = 1999 | pages = 956\u2013978 | place = Johannesburg   | publisher = BirdLife South Africa}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour==\n[[File:Yellow-faced Honeyeater lambertia.jpg|thumb|Piercing the base of a mountain devil (''Lambertia formosa'') flower to feed on nectar]]\nThe yellow-faced honeyeater is usually seen singly, in pairs or in small family groups, when not migrating.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=724}} They forage as individuals, as pairs or as small groups of up to ten birds, and during migration in larger groups. They sometimes feed in large, [[mixed-species foraging flock | mixed-species, foraging flock]]s, composed predominately of insectivorous birds.{{sfn|Higgins|Christidis|Ford|2008|p=597}}\n\n===Feeding===\nComparatively short-billed for a honeyeater, the yellow-faced honeyeater is thought to have adapted to a mixed diet.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=730}} Its diet consists of [[nectar]], [[pollen]], fruit, seeds, [[Honeydew (secretion)|honeydew]], and insects. It is arboreal, foraging primarily among the foliage and flowers of trees, shrubs, and [[mistletoe]]s, less often on branches and tree-trunk, and rarely on the ground.<ref name=Bounds>{{cite journal| last = Bounds| first = Jenny| title = Lone Fuscous and Yellow-faced Honeyeaters keeping company| journal = Canberra Bird Notes | volume = 21| issue = 1| page = 14 | year = 1996 | issn = 0314-8211}}</ref> Yellow-faced honeyeaters feed on nectar around 40% of the time, and on insects around 60% of the time.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=730}} The yellow-faced honeyeater feeds on insects by [[Gleaning (birds)|gleaning]], [[Hawking (birds)|sallying]], catching in flight, or probing in bark crevices. The insects eaten are primarily [[Diptera]] (flies, mosquitoes, maggots, gnats, and midges), [[beetle]]s, and [[spider]]s.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=731}} A study of the pollen on the bills and foreheads of captured birds found that 70% carried pollen from silver banksia (''[[Banksia marginata]]''), 61% from heath-leaved banksia (''[[Banksia ericifolia]]''), and 22% carried pollen from other plants in the area including fern-leaved banksia (''[[Banksia oblongifolia]]''), mountain devil (''[[Lambertia formosa]]''), and green spider-flower (''[[Grevillea mucronulata]]'').\n\nIn April and May, before the autumn migration, the yellow-faced honeyeater increases its nectar consumption, which increases its body mass. The average body mass in late autumn of {{convert|17.5|g|oz}} is 13% higher than the average recorded between January and April, and the yellow-faced honeyeater begins the migration with healthy fat reserves.{{sfn|Munro|2003|p=148}}\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Yellow-faced-honeyeater.jpg|thumb|alt=A yellow-faced honeyeater feeding its chicks in a nest in a rose bush| Three chicks are raised in a flimsy nest in a garden shrub.]]\nThe yellow-faced honeyeater breeds in [[Monogamy in animals|monogamous]] pairs in a breeding season that extends from July to March, with migrating birds nesting later than sedentary birds.<ref name=\"Clarke\"/> They nest solitarily in all-purpose [[Territory (animal)|territories]] that both parents defend against conspecifics and other species including [[Acanthiza|thornbills]], [[spinebill]]s and silvereyes, although the male is involved in more aggressive interactions than the female.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=732}} Within a breeding season, females lay two or three clutches of eggs, re-nesting with the same partner in the same territory. [[Bird ringing|Banded]] birds have been identified in the same territory for periods of up to five years.<ref name=\"Clarke\" />\n\nThe nest is built in the understorey shrubs, relatively close to the ground. Nests have been recorded in prickly coprosma (''[[Coprosma quadrifida]]''), ''[[Cassinia]]'', tea-trees (''[[Melaleuca]]''), [[eucalypt]]s and [[acacia]]s, as well as in garden shrubs.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=733}} The nest is a fragile, cup-shaped structure, swollen at the sides and narrower at the rim. The female builds the nest, but is often accompanied by the male as she gathers nesting material. Most nests are built of greenish material, which varies with the location; in coastal areas, grass is the primary material; in mountain forests, the nest is often covered with moss.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=734}} One bird was recorded repeatedly flying between the nest and a [[koala]] {{convert|36|m|ft}} away and plucking the long hair near its ears to incorporate in the nest.<ref name=Cody>{{cite journal| last = Cody | first = M.L. | title = Honeyeater plucks koala for nest material | journal = Emu | volume = 91 | issue = 2 | pages = 125\u2013126 | year = 1991 | doi = 10.1071/MU9910125}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.audubon.org/news/honeyeaters-steal-fur-sleeping-koalas-their-nests|title=Honeyeaters Steal Fur from Sleeping Koalas for Their Nests|date=2017-08-23|website=Audubon|language=en|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref> The nests are very fine, with the eggs visible through the gauze-like walls, and they sometimes fall apart. They have been known to disintegrate with eggs and nestlings falling through the bottom.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=734}}\n\nThe female undertakes the [[avian incubation|incubation]] alone.<ref name=\"Clarke\"/> Eggs are oval, approximately {{convert|21|mm|in}} long and {{convert|14|mm|in}} wide, and pinkish white in colour with spots and blotches of dark reddish-brown.{{sfn|Beruldsen|1980|p=371}} The [[clutch (eggs)|clutch]] size varies from one to three eggs, and eggs take around two weeks to hatch. Upon hatching, both parents feed the nestlings and remove [[Feces|faecal pellets]]. The chicks [[fledge]] after thirteen days, and leave the parental territory after a further two weeks. The success rate can be as low as 16% of eggs developing into fledged young, with nest failure, hot weather, heavy rain, human activity (including fungicide spraying and nest damage), egg destruction by [[brood parasite]]s, and [[predation]] by [[Pseudonaja|brown snakes]], cats, and [[currawong]]s, all recorded as contributing to brood failure.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=735}} Among the species that parasitize the nests of yellow-faced honeyeaters are [[fan-tailed cuckoo]]s, [[brush cuckoo]]s, [[pallid cuckoo]]s, [[shining bronze-cuckoo]]s, and [[Horsfield's bronze-cuckoo]]s.{{sfn|Higgins|Christidis|Ford|2008|p=597}} The yellow-faced honeyeater promptly nests again after both successful and failed breeding attempts.<ref name=Boulton>{{cite journal| last = Boulton | first = R.L| last2 = Cassey |first2=P. |last3=Schipper |first3=C. |last4=Clarke |first4=M.F. | title = Nest site selection by Yellow-faced Honeyeaters ''Lichenostomus chrysops'' | journal = Journal of Avian Biology | volume = 34 | pages = 267\u2013274  | year = 2003 | issn = 0908-8857| doi = 10.1034/j.1600-048X.2003.03062.x| issue = 3}}</ref>\n\nA paternity analysis of yellow-faced honeyeater nestlings found that 10 of 18 nestlings were fathered by the male of the nesting pair, with clear evidence for extra-pair paternity in the case of the remaining 44%. This conflicts with the usual pattern, where genetic [[monogamy]] is linked to the characteristics of strong social pairing, essential paternal contributions to brood-rearing, and to sexual [[Monomorphism (biology)|monomorphism]];<ref name= \"Ewen\">{{cite journal |author1=Ewen, John G. |author2=Ciborowski, Kate L. |author3=Clarke, Rohan H. |author4=Boulton, Rebecca L. |author5=Clarke, Michael F. | year = 2008| title = Evidence of extra-pair paternity in two socially monogamous Australian passerines: the Crescent Honeyeater and the Yellow-faced Honeyeater | journal = Emu | volume =108| pages =133\u2013137 | doi =10.1071/MU07040 |issue= 2}}</ref> characteristics that are exhibited by the [[yellow honeyeater]], for example.\n\n==Conservation status==\nSeveral [[Parasitism|ectoparasites]], which can affect survival and reproductive fitness, have been found on the yellow-faced honeyeater: the mites, [[Rhinonyssidae|''Ptilonyssus meliphagae'']] and ''Ptilonyssus thymanzae'', and ''[[Ixodes]]'' species ticks.{{sfn|Higgins|Peter|Steele|2001|p=1262}}\n\nIn general, honeyeaters require extensive [[Wildlife corridor|corridors]] of mature trees along their migratory routes, and flowering woodlands for nesting, so they are vulnerable to the effects of land-clearing, grazing and weed infestation. The woodland habitat they prefer is considered an endangered ecological community. As it is common and widespread, the yellow-faced honeyeater is considered by the [[IUCN]] to be of [[least concern]] for conservation.<ref name=IUCN/> A field experiment to determine whether yellow-faced honeyeater nests were less successful in fragmented habitats found that nests closer to forest margins actually had a higher success rate than those deeper in the forest. However, the yellow-faced honeyeater tends to nest away from the edge of forest remnants; experiments with natural and artificial nests at varying distances from the open areas showed no increase in the number of avian predators at the forest edge. The results of the field experiment did not support the \"[[ecological trap]]\" and \"predator influx\" theories, and contribute to a belief that [[Habitat fragmentation|fragmented habitats]] may not be as problematic as previously thought.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Do yellow-faced honeyeater (''Lichenostomus chrysops'') nests experience higher predation at forest edges? |last1=Boulton | first1=R.L. | last2=Clarke | first2=M.F. | journal =Wildlife Research | year= 2003 |volume=30| issue=2| pages=119\u2013125 | doi=10.1071/WR02055}}</ref><!-- cites prev 3 sentences --> In some areas, the species is considered a pest because of its intrusion into orchards and urban gardens, where it damages fruit.{{sfn|Officer|1965|p=50}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book |last=Beruldsen |first=Gordon |authorlink=Gordon Beruldsen |year=1980 |title=A Field Guide to Nests and Eggs of Australian Birds |location=Adelaide, S.A. |publisher=Rigby |isbn=978-0-7270-1202-9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Higgins |first=Peter |first2=J. M. |last2=Peter |last3=Steele |first3=W. K. |year=2001 |contribution=''Lichenostomus chrysops'' Yellow-faced Honeyeater |title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds Volume 5: Tyrant-flycatchers to Chats |location=Melbourne, Vic. |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=724\u2013740 |isbn=978-0-19-553071-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Higgins |first=Peter |last2=Christidis |first2=Les |last3=Ford |first3=Hugh |year=2008 |contribution=Family Meliphagidae (Honeyeaters) |editor-last=Josep |editor-first=del Hoyo |editor2-last=Andrew |editor2-first=Elliott |editor3-last=David |editor3-first=Christie |title=Handbook of the Birds of the World Volume 13: Penduline-tits to Shrikes |title-link=Handbook of the Birds of the World |place=Barcelona |publisher=Lynx Edicions |pages=597\u2013598 |isbn=978-84-96553-45-3  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |first=Ursula |last=Munro |year=2003 |contribution=Life History and Ecophysical Adaptations to Migration in Australian Birds |editor-last=Berthold |editor-first=Peter |editor2-last=Gwinner |editor2-first=Eberhard |editor3-last=Sonnenschein |editor3-first=E. |title=Avian Migration |place=New York |publisher=Springer-Verlag |pages=141\u2013154 |isbn=978-3-540-43408-5  |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Officer |first=Hugh R. |year=1965 |title=Australian Honeyeaters |location=Melbourne, Vic. |publisher=The Bird Observers Club, Melbourne |isbn=978-0-909711-03-0 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Caligavis chrysops}}\n{{Wikispecies|Caligavis chrysops}}\n\n* [http://www.xeno-canto.org/species/Caligavis-chrysops Xeno-canto: audio recordings of the yellow-faced honeyeater]\n* {{cite web | title=Yellow-faced Honeyeaters spring migration: Podcast | publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation: Radio National | url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/breakfast/stories/2011/3319096.htm | date=16 September 2011 }}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27075233}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:honeyeater, yellow-faced}}\n[[Category:Caligavis|yellow-faced honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Birds of Queensland]]\n[[Category:Birds of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Birds of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1801|yellow-faced honeyeater]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eConservation status:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yellow-faced_honeyeater"}
{"title_page": "Treaty of Vereeniging", "text_new": "{{Use South African English |date=December 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox treaty\n |name            = Treaty of Vereeniging\n |image           = Table where treaty was signed.JPG\n |caption         = [[Melrose House]], [[Pretoria]]\n |context         = End of the [[Second Boer War]]\n |date_signed     = 31 May 1902\n |location_signed = [[Melrose House]], [[Pretoria]], {{nowr|[[South African Republic]]}}\n |signatories     = \n* {{flagdeco|UKGBI}} Sir [[Alfred Milner, 1st Viscount Milner|Alfred Milner]]\n* {{flagdeco|UKGBI}} [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Lord Kitchener]]\n* {{flagdeco|ZAR}} [[Schalk Willem Burger]]\n* {{flagdeco|ZAR}} [[Francis William Reitz]]\n* {{flagdeco|ZAR}} [[Louis Botha]]\n* {{flagdeco|ZAR}} [[Koos de la Rey]]\n* {{flagdeco|ZAR}} Lucas Johannes Meyer\n* {{flagdeco|ZAR}} [[Johannes Christoffel Krogh]]\n* {{flagdeco|OVS}} [[Christiaan de Wet]]\n* {{flagdeco|OVS}} [[J. B. M. Hertzog]]\n* {{flagdeco|OVS}} C. H. Olivier\n* {{flagdeco|OVS}} W. C. J. Bebner\n |parties         = {{ubl|{{flagcountry|UKGBI}}|{{flagcountry|ZAR}}|{{flagcountry|OVS}}}}\n |wikisource      = Peace of Vereeniging\n}}\n\nThe '''Treaty of Vereeniging''' was a [[peace treaty]], signed on 31 May 1902, that ended the [[Second Boer War]] between the [[South African Republic]] and the [[Orange Free State]], on the one side, and the United Kingdom on the other.\n\nThis settlement provided for the end of hostilities and eventual self-government to the Transvaal (South African Republic) and the Orange Free State as colonies of the United Kingdom. The Boer republics agreed to come under the sovereignty of the British Crown and the British government agreed on various details.\n\n==Background==\nOn 9 April 1902, with safe passage guaranteed by the British, the Boer leadership met at [[Klerksdorp]], [[South African Republic|Transvaal]]. Present were [[Marthinus Steyn]], Free State president and [[Schalk Willem Burger|Schalk Burger]] acting Transvaal president with the Boer generals [[Louis Botha]], [[Jan Smuts]], [[Christiaan de Wet]] and [[Koos de la Rey]] and they would discuss the progress of the war and whether negotiations should be opened with the British.<ref name=\"Meredith\">{{cite book | title=Diamonds, Gold and War. The Making of South Africa | publisher=Simon & Schuster | author=Meredith, Martin | year=2007 | location=London, Great Britain | isbn=978-0-7432-8614-5}}</ref>{{rp|462}}\n\nOn 12 April, a ten-man Boer delegation went to [[Melrose House]] in [[Pretoria]] and met General [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Kitchener]] bringing with them a seven-point proposal for a treaty of friendship. Their position was to return to a pre-war status-quo for the republics with certain changes such as a commercial union with the British colonies, votes for ''[[uitlander]]s'', equal languages in schools and an amnesty.<ref name=Meredith/>{{rp|462}} Kitchener was astounded but forwarded the proposal to London, knowing it would not be accepted but wanted the dialogue between the two parties to continue.<ref name=Meredith/>{{rp|462}} [[Alfred Milner, 1st Viscount Milner|Alfred Milner]] joined the negotiations on 14 April but he was hostile to the Boers and wanted an unconditional surrender and a free rein in administering the two republics as colonies.<ref name=Meredith/>{{rp|463}} The British government rejected the Boers' terms and the delegation asked Kitchener for a series of armistices so that they could return and consult with the commandos as to whether they could negotiate a surrender and its terms.<ref name=Meredith/>{{rp|463}}\n\nOn 15 May, the commandos elected 30 delegates from each pre-war republic and they met at [[Vereeniging]]. The debate was heated, split between the Transvaalers who wanted an end to the war as living conditions for the Boer civilians in the Transvaal were becoming desperate with splits developing in the Boer population there, while the Free Staters wished to continue the war.<ref name=Meredith/>{{rp|463\u20134}}\n\nA compromise was reached and the generals returned to Pretoria on 19 May with a proposal that the republics remain independent, with foreign relations and self-government under British control, cede control of [[Swaziland]] and relinquish control of the [[Witwatersrand]] goldfields.<ref name=Meredith/>{{rp|464}} The terms were rejected by Kitchener and Milner with the two of them disagreeing on the direction of the future, with the former seeking reconciliation and the latter seeking humiliation.<ref name=Meredith/>{{rp|465}} The debate between the Boer generals and British delegation would continue for days. The British made concessions which included the Cape rebels only being disenfranchised for five years.<ref name=Meredith/>{{rp|465}} The issue of black enfranchisement was settled, when Chamberlain's argument before the war for black people's political rights to be considered at the end of the war was ignored in the interest of reconciliation, and Smuts was able to include a clause that the argument for black enfranchisement would be decided when self-government was realised for the Transvaal and Free State.<ref name=Meredith/>{{rp|465\u20136}} As to the contentious issue of British and Boer war debt and promissory notes, Botha wanted \u20a43 million while the British offered \u20a41 million, with Milner angry at the idea of paying for Boer promissory notes, but Kitchener agreed seeing Botha's viewpoint that it would strengthen the latter in negotiating the terms with his delegates.<ref name=Meredith/>{{rp|466}} The Orange River and the Transvaal colonies would first be administered by a British military administration, then by civilians and then at some point in the future via self-government.<ref name=Meredith/>{{rp|467}}\n\nOn 27 May 1902, the British Cabinet met to discuss the final terms of the treaty and on 28 May in Pretoria, the Boers were presented with the terms and given three days to make a decision of which the answer required was either yes or no.<ref name=Meredith/>{{rp|466\u20137}}\n\nSixty Boer delegates met in Vereeniging to debate the terms of the treaty and a heated debate developed between the Transvaalers and Free Staters, with Botha and Smuts arguing in favour while Marthinus Steyn argued against it.<ref name=Meredith/>{{rp|467}} Ill, he would resign as Free State president after the first day of debate and advised Chistiaan de Wet if the Transvaalers agreed to the treaty, then he should too as Free State could not continue the war on their own.<ref name=Meredith/>{{rp|468}}\n\nAt around 2 pm on 31 May 1902 a vote was called and 54 delegates voted yes to the terms of the treaty but six voted no. On the same day the Boer leaders returned to Kitchener at Melrose House in Pretoria and the peace treaty was signed.<ref name=Meredith/>{{rp|469}}\n\n== Terms of the settlement ==\nThis settlement entailed the end of hostilities and the surrender of all Boer forces and their arms to the British, with the promise of eventual self-government to the Transvaal ([[South African Republic]]) and the [[Orange Free State]] as [[colony|colonies]] of the [[British Empire]]. The [[Boer Republics]] agreed to come under the [[sovereignty]] of the British Crown and the British government agreed on various details including the following:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/archive/peace-treaty-vereeniging-original-document|title=Peace Treaty of Vereeniging \u2013 original document|website=South African History Online|access-date=30 May 2018}}</ref>\n# All Boer fighters of both republics had to give themselves up\n# All combatants would be disarmed\n# Everyone had to swear allegiance to the Crown\n# No death penalties would be dealt out\n# A general amnesty would apply\n# The use of [[Dutch language|Dutch]] would be allowed in the schools and law courts\n# To eventually give the [[Transvaal Colony|Transvaal]] and the [[Orange Free State]] [[self-governance|self-government]] (civil government was granted in 1906 and 1907, respectively)<ref>{{cite book |title=The Unification of South Africa, 1902\u20131910 |url=https://archive.org/details/unificationofsou0000thom |url-access=registration |first=L. M. |last=Thompson |year=1960 |publisher=Clarendon Press |location=Oxford }}</ref>\n# To avoid discussing the native (Black) [[suffrage|enfranchisement]] issue until self-government had been given\n# To pay the [[Afrikaner]]s \u00a33,000,000 in reconstruction aid\n# Property rights of Boers would be respected\n# No land taxes would be introduced\n# Registered private guns would be allowed\n\nSubsequent to the British government giving the [[Boer]] colonies self-government, the [[Union of South Africa]] was created on 31 May 1910. The Union gained relative independence under the 1926 [[Imperial Conference]] and the 1931 [[Statute of Westminster 1931|Statute of Westminster]]. The country became a republic in 1961 therefore severing all connections with Great Britain. The country rejoined the Commonwealth in 1994.\n\nAlthough the treaty is named after the town of [[Vereeniging]] in Transvaal, where the peace negotiations took place, the document was actually signed at [[Melrose House]] in [[Pretoria]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Pretoria Convention]]\n* [[History of South Africa]]\n* [[Military history of South Africa]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author1=Davenport, T.|author2=C. Saunders|title=South Africa: A Modern History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UgaMDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA233|year=2000|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|page=233ff}}\n* Ebrahim, Hassen. ''The soul of a nation: Constitution-making in South Africa.'' (Oxford UP, 1998).\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikisource|Peace of Vereeniging}}\n* {{Gutenberg|no=27529|name=The Peace Negotiations between the Governments of the South African Republic and the Orange Free State, and the Representatives of the British Government}}\n\n{{Political history of South Africa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vereeniging, Treaty}}\n[[Category:History of Pretoria]]\n[[Category:Second Boer War|Treaty of Vereeniging]]\n[[Category:Vereeniging|Treaty of Vereeniging]]\n[[Category:1902 in South Africa|Treaty of Vereeniging]]\n[[Category:South Africa\u2013United Kingdom relations|Treaty of Vereeniging]]\n[[Category:Peace treaties of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Peace treaties of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Treaties concluded in 1902]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the Orange Free State]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the South African Republic]]\n[[Category:1902 in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the United Kingdom (1801\u20131922)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use South African English |date=December 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates |date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox treaty\n |name            = Treaty of Vereeniging\n |image           = Table where treaty was signed.JPG\n |caption         = [[Melrose House]], [[Pretoria]]\n |context         = End of the [[Second Boer War]]\n |date_signed     = 31 May 1902\n |location_signed = [[Melrose House]], [[Pretoria]], {{nowr|[[South African Republic]]}}\n |signatories     = \n* {{flagdeco|UKGBI}} Sir [[Alfred Milner, 1st Viscount Milner|Alfred Milner]]\n* {{flagdeco|UKGBI}} [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Lord Kitchener]]\n* {{flagdeco|ZAR}} [[Schalk Willem Burger]]\n* {{flagdeco|ZAR}} [[Francis William Reitz]]\n* {{flagdeco|ZAR}} [[Louis Botha]]\n* {{flagdeco|ZAR}} [[Koos de la Rey]]\n* {{flagdeco|ZAR}} Lucas Johannes Meyer\n* {{flagdeco|ZAR}} [[Johannes Christoffel Krogh]]\n* {{flagdeco|OVS}} [[Christiaan de Wet]]\n* {{flagdeco|OVS}} [[J. B. M. Hertzog]]\n* {{flagdeco|OVS}} C. H. Olivier\n* {{flagdeco|OVS}} W. C. J. Bebner\n |parties         = {{ubl|{{flagcountry|UKGBI}}|{{flagcountry|ZAR}}|{{flagcountry|OVS}}}}\n |wikisource      = Peace of Vereeniging\n}}\n\nThe '''Treaty of Vereeniging''' was a [[peace treaty]], signed on